Target: `module/LLMWorkflow/retrieval/RetrievalCache.ps1`

Reason:
- surface meaningful cleanup failures in atomic cache writes
- keep optional path probes quiet, but stop silently swallowing temp-file removal failure after cache write failure

---

## Patch A: keep quiet fallback path resolution probes unchanged

These are acceptable low-value probes and do not need churn in this pass:

```powershell
$resolvedRoot = Resolve-Path -Path $ProjectRoot -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
if (-not $resolvedRoot) {
    $resolvedRoot = $ProjectRoot
}
```

## Patch B: surface temp-file cleanup failure in `Write-CacheFile`

Current code:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file on error
    if (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempFile) {
        Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempFile -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
    }
    throw "Failed to write cache file: $_"
}
```

Replace with:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file on error
    if ($tempFile -and (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempFile)) {
        try {
            Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempFile -Force -ErrorAction Stop
        }
        catch {
            Write-Warning "[RetrievalCache] Failed to remove temporary cache file '$tempFile' after write failure: $($_.Exception.Message)"
        }
    }
    throw "Failed to write cache file: $_"
}
```

Why this matters:
- failed cache writes already represent a degraded state
- silently leaving orphan temp files behind creates exactly the kind of hidden operational residue this remediation pass is meant to expose

## Patch C: optional diagnostics tightening in `Read-CacheFile`

Current code:

```powershell
catch {
    Write-Verbose "[RetrievalCache] Skipping invalid cache line: $_"
}
```

Recommended tightening:

```powershell
catch {
    Write-Verbose "[RetrievalCache] Skipping invalid cache line: $($_.Exception.Message)"
}
```

This is not a behavior change, but it keeps noisy exception formatting out of routine diagnostics.
